Literature

AVL, Routing & Scheduling Case Study: Gaining Real-time Delivery Insight with Intelligent AVL


Intelligent AVL provides a Web-based view of real-time information on delivery arrivals at distribution centers or hubs, enabling dispatchers to adapt routes quickly and efficiently according to exceptions.x


Challenges of the Logistics Industry 


Market leading Logistics Service Providers are offsetting challenges such as changes in fuel rates, increasing competition and a fluctuating freight rate market by “plugging in” to global opportunities. View statistics and macro trends in the form of an infographic and learn how LSPs are balancing operational excellence with profitability.


Fuel & Labor Cost Savings through Next Generation Fleet Management System Best Practices


Next Generation Fleet Management System Best Practices delineates the best practices fleet managers can implement to work better and smarter, and to significantly reduce fleet costs.


Optimizing Home Delivery: Winning Market Share Through Efficient Home Delivery Programs


This white paper shows how home delivery providers can transform the delivery service from a costly liability to a customer service asset while controlling and minimizing transportation costs.
View More ResourceseLearning

FMCSA ELD Mandate: Final Ruling on Electronic Logging Devices


The Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration (FMCSA) recently released the final ruling on mandating electronic logbooks for commercial vehicle drivers working in the U.S. It also applies to truck and bus drivers from Mexico and Canada who cross into the U.S. and operate a commercial vehicle.


Logistics Accounting for Freight Forwarders


Incorporating techniques to derive revenue at multiple junctures is essential for freight forwarders in order to better compete.


Transportation Management System (TMS): The ‘secret sauce’ is more affordable and functional than ever


Benefits of Transportation Management Systems, commonly known as TMS. TMS software automates such functions as carrier selection, routing and rating; in the process, it helps users reduce their shipping and labor costs.


Electronic Driver Logs are on the Way


The US federal government’s regulations mandating the use of Electronic Logging Devices, also known as Electronic On-Board Recorders (EOBRs), in trucks are expected to take effect sometime next year. Once it does, all carriers and drivers governed by the federal Hours-of-Service rules must be in compliance within two years of the 2015 effective date.
